---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
import PageMeta from '@/components/PageMeta.astro';
import fs from 'node:fs';
import path from 'node:path';

// Live counts from the *tracked* mapping file only (source/03-standards/rml/build/
// is gitignored harness output and cannot safely be read at site-build time — see
// ADR-0059 §Decision Outcome).
const RML = path.resolve(process.cwd(), 'source/03-standards/rml');

function read(name: string): string {
  try { return fs.readFileSync(path.join(RML, name), 'utf8'); } catch { return ''; }
}
function countMatches(text: string, re: RegExp): number {
  const m = text.match(re);
  return m ? m.length : 0;
}

const mappingTtl = read('mapping/opda-pdtf.rml.ttl');
const counts = {
  triplesMaps: countMatches(mappingTtl, /a rr:TriplesMap/g),
  predicateObjectMaps: countMatches(mappingTtl, /rr:predicateObjectMap/g),
};
---
<Layout
  title="Mapping"
  description="The RML mapping that traces the OPDA ontology to its PDTF JSON Schema origin and back — an independent, machine-checked bridge between /ontology and /schema."
>
<PageMeta category="Section overview" variant="brand" updated="Updated 2026-07-05" damaKa={["Metadata Management", "Data Integration & Interoperability"]} />

  <h1>Mapping</h1>

  <p class="lead">
    <a href="/ontology">Ontology</a> and <a href="/schema">Schema</a> are two independent
    accounts of the same PDTF data — one in OWL/RDF, one in JSON Schema. This section
    documents the <strong>RML mapping</strong>: a machine-checked bridge between them,
    tracing every ontology term back to the exact schema location it was minted from, and
    every schema location forward to the ontology term (if any) that represents it.
  </p>

  <nav class="callout callout--note" aria-label="On this page">
    <div class="callout__label">On this page</div>
    <ul style="margin: 0;">
      <li><a href="#why">Why a second provenance mechanism</a></li>
      <li><a href="#stats">The mapping, by the numbers</a></li>
      <li><a href="#explore">Explore this section</a></li>
    </ul>
  </nav>

  <h2 id="why">Why a second provenance mechanism</h2>
  <p>
    Every <code>opda:</code> term already carries a <code>dct:source</code> citation to its
    authoritative origin (see <a href="/ontology/provenance">Decision provenance</a>). But
    <code>dct:source</code> is single-valued — it can answer <em>which one source defines
    this term's meaning</em>, but not <em>everywhere this term's data actually occurs</em>,
    and nothing about that convention alone independently checks that a citation resolves to
    something real.
  </p>
  <p>
    <a class="resource-link" href="/modelling/odr/odr-0035">ODR-0035</a> adopted
    <a href="https://rml.io" target="_blank" rel="noopener">RML</a> (RDF Mapping Language) to
    close that gap: a second, independent, bidirectional trace, checked two ways — every
    schema location the mapping cites resolves in the real PDTF v3 schema, and every ontology
    term it addresses is a real, declared <code>opda:</code> term. The two mechanisms are
    expected to <em>usually</em> agree (68 of 73 directly comparable predicates did, when
    checked) but are verified independently and are not required to. The audit that motivated
    this caught real, pre-existing defects — 8 stale-path and 16 unresolved
    <code>dct:source</code> citations — that the ontology generator's own emission process had
    never verified.
  </p>

  <div class="callout callout--key">
    <div class="callout__label">Documentation, not ETL</div>
    <p>
      The mapping consumes a PDTF v3 transaction instance and emits RDF purely to
      <strong>verify</strong> the schema↔ontology correspondence — it is not, and must not
      become, an executable pipeline against real transaction data
      (<a href="/modelling/odr/odr-0035">ODR-0035</a> §Rules). No instance data is required
      for, or produced by, the primary validation gate.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="stats">The mapping, by the numbers</h2>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Count</th><th>Source</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>rr:TriplesMap</code> rules</td><td>{counts.triplesMaps}</td><td><code>mapping/opda-pdtf.rml.ttl</code> — live</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>rr:predicateObjectMap</code> entries</td><td>{counts.predicateObjectMaps}</td><td><code>mapping/opda-pdtf.rml.ttl</code> — live</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Domain-module resources mapped</td><td>466 / 469 (99.4%)</td><td><code>build/final-gap.json</code>, as of 2026-07-05 — see <a href="/mapping/coverage">Coverage &amp; gaps</a></td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p class="muted tiny">
    The first two rows are counted live from the committed mapping file at build time. The
    coverage row is <strong>not</strong> live — it's the output of a separate harness whose
    build artefacts are gitignored, cited here with its regeneration command on
    <a href="/mapping/validate">Running &amp; validating</a>. And 469 is the curated
    domain-module resource count, not the raw 8,458-leaf schema dictionary — see
    <a href="/mapping/coverage#scope">why that's the right denominator</a>.
  </p>

  <div class="callout callout--note">
    <div class="callout__label">See also — a different "mapping"</div>
    <p>
      <a href="/modelling/jsonld-mappings">JSON-LD mappings</a> is a separate, still-unbuilt
      workstream: per-overlay <code>@context</code> files for production JSON-LD
      round-tripping (BASPI v5 first). It solves a different problem for a different
      audience — this section is the internal, already-largely-complete verification trace;
      that one is external data-interop tooling yet to be built.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="explore">Explore this section</h2>
  <div class="card-grid">
    <a class="card" href="/mapping/how-it-works">
      <div class="pill pill--info">Engineering</div>
      <h3>How it works</h3>
      <p>RMLMapper + Jena validation, the two checking gates, and the enum→SKOS-concept-IRI technique.</p>
    </a>
    <a class="card" href="/mapping/coverage">
      <div class="pill pill--info">99.4%</div>
      <h3>Coverage &amp; gaps</h3>
      <p>What's mapped, what's genuinely out of scope, and the honest-non-mapping discipline.</p>
    </a>
    <a class="card" href="/mapping/validate">
      <div class="pill pill--info">Reproduce</div>
      <h3>Running &amp; validating</h3>
      <p>The make targets, the file layout, and links into the real harness files.</p>
    </a>
  </div>
</Layout>
